<paragraph blockId="2.[189,1399,1768,2006]" lastBlockId="3.[189,1399,267,364]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="4" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Detailed diagnoses and descriptions of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lepeletier" authorityYear="1841" box="[644,745,1768,1794]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[644,745,1768,1794]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Scrapter</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Eardley C. D." box="[961,1140,1768,1795]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="37 - 92" refId="ref26876" refString="Eardley C. D. 1996. The genus Scrapter Lepeletier &amp; Serville (Hymenoptera: Colletidae). African Entomology 4: 37 - 92." type="journal article" year="1996">Eardley (1996)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Engel" box="[1150,1306,1768,1795]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 33" refId="ref26933" refString="Engel, M. S. 2005. Family-group names for bees (Hymenoptera: Apoidea). American Museum Novitates 3476: 1 - 33." type="journal article" year="2005">Engel (2005)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Davies G. B. P. &amp; Brothers D. J." pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="135 - 183" refId="ref26766" refString="Davies G. B. P. &amp; Brothers D. J. 2006. Morphology of Scrapter (Hymenoptera: Anthophila: Colletidae), with description of three new species and taxonomic status of five Cockerell taxa. African Invertebrates 47: 135 - 183." type="journal article" year="2006">Davies &amp; Brothers (2006)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Michener C. D." box="[472,676,1803,1829]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" refId="ref27318" refString="Michener C. D. 2007. The Bees of the World. 2 nd edition, Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore, Maryland." type="book" year="2007">Michener (2007)</bibRefCitation>
, so they are not repeated here. Regarding the availability of Scrapterini 
<emphasis box="[328,403,1839,1864]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">versus</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ascher &amp; Engel" authorityYear="2005" box="[412,546,1838,1864]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Scraptrinae">Scraptrinae</taxonomicName>
see 
<bibRefCitation author="Ascher J. S. &amp; Engel M. S." box="[602,888,1838,1865]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="117 - 119" refId="ref26606" refString="Ascher J. S. &amp; Engel M. S. 2006. On the availability of family-group names based on Scrapter (Hymenoptera: Colletidae). Entomological News 117: 117 - 119." type="journal article" year="2006">Ascher &amp; Engel (2006)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lepeletier" authorityYear="1841" box="[901,1002,1839,1865]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[901,1002,1839,1865]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Scrapter</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows an unusual level of intrageneric diversity, described in detail by 
<bibRefCitation author="Davies G. B. P. &amp; Brothers D. J." box="[671,986,1873,1900]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="135 - 183" refId="ref26766" refString="Davies G. B. P. &amp; Brothers D. J. 2006. Morphology of Scrapter (Hymenoptera: Anthophila: Colletidae), with description of three new species and taxonomic status of five Cockerell taxa. African Invertebrates 47: 135 - 183." type="journal article" year="2006">Davies &amp; Brothers (2006)</bibRefCitation>
, so various authors suggested that after revision the genus could be split up into several (sub)genera (
<bibRefCitation author="Engel" box="[1009,1152,1909,1936]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 33" refId="ref26933" refString="Engel, M. S. 2005. Family-group names for bees (Hymenoptera: Apoidea). American Museum Novitates 3476: 1 - 33." type="journal article" year="2005">Engel 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Melo G. A. R. &amp; Goncalves R. B." pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="153 - 159" refId="ref27255" refString="Melo G. A. R. &amp; Goncalves R. B. 2005. Higher level bee classifications. Revista Brasileira de Zoologia 22: 153 - 159." type="journal article" year="2005">Melo &amp; Gonçalves 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Michener C. D." box="[267,454,1944,1970]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" refId="ref27318" refString="Michener C. D. 2007. The Bees of the World. 2 nd edition, Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore, Maryland." type="book" year="2007">Michener 2007</bibRefCitation>
). The current system of species-groups suggested by 
<bibRefCitation author="Eardley C. D." box="[1105,1285,1944,1971]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="37 - 92" refId="ref26876" refString="Eardley C. D. 1996. The genus Scrapter Lepeletier &amp; Serville (Hymenoptera: Colletidae). African Entomology 4: 37 - 92." type="journal article" year="1996">Eardley (1996)</bibRefCitation>
does not convincingly reflect this diversity, as it partly contains morphologically heterogenous and presumably paraphyletic species-groups. The 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1934" box="[606,776,267,294]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavostictus">
<emphasis box="[606,776,267,294]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">S. flavostictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group is an example of such an inhomogeneous assemblage and includes the first described &quot;euryglossiform&quot; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lepeletier" authorityYear="1841" box="[905,1006,303,329]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[905,1006,303,329]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Scrapter</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Friese" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[1020,1159,303,329]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albitarsis">
<emphasis box="[1020,1159,303,329]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">S. albitarsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This species and its relatives are here transferred to a new species-group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,689,403,429]" box="[189,689,403,429]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,689,403,429]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,689,403,429]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
The group of &quot;euryglossiform&quot; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lepeletier" authorityYear="1841" box="[586,689,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[586,689,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Scrapter</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,1399,450,687]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
The term &quot;euryglossiform&quot; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lepeletier" authorityYear="1841" box="[523,624,450,476]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[523,624,450,476]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Scrapter</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is introduced here for a group of morphologically monotonous species, including the smallest bees of the genus (3.5–7.0 mm), that are predominantly black, often with yellow markings on the legs. This species-group can also be referred to as the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Friese" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[1172,1313,520,547]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albitarsis">
<emphasis box="[1172,1313,520,547]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">S. albitarsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group, named after the first described species. In their body shape, sparse pilosity, surface sculpture and narrow groove-like facial fovea they superficially resemble andreniform 
<taxonomicName box="[940,1110,590,616]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Euryglossinae">Euryglossinae</taxonomicName>
. These similarities might be convergent (
<bibRefCitation author="Michener C. D." box="[367,607,626,652]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refId="ref27318" refString="Michener C. D. 2007. The Bees of the World. 2 nd edition, Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore, Maryland." type="book" year="2007">Michener 2007: 171</bibRefCitation>
) but potentially reflect the presumed sister-group relationship of the Australian 
<taxonomicName box="[319,485,661,687]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Euryglossinae">Euryglossinae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Almeida &amp; Danforth 2009)" baseAuthorityName="Almeida &amp; Danforth" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[542,1016,661,687]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Scraptrinae">
Scraptrinae (
<bibRefCitation author="Almeida E. A. B. &amp; Danforth B. N." box="[690,1008,661,687]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="290 - 309" refId="ref26566" refString="Almeida E. A. B. &amp; Danforth B. N. 2009. Phylogeny of colletid bees (Hymenoptera: Colletidae) inferred from four nuclear genes. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 50: 290 - 309." type="journal article" year="2009">Almeida &amp; Danforth 2009</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,1399,726,1034]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
The species of the &quot;euryglossiform&quot; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lepeletier" authorityYear="1841" box="[635,736,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[635,736,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Scrapter</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are characterized by a) a sulcus-like facial fovea with an invisible bottom as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1793" box="[501,597,762,788]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Hylaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[501,597,762,788]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Hylaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[677,771,761,788]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[189,232,1902,1928]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,527,1857]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[189,1399,527,1858]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 1. Scrapter acanthophorus Davies, 2005, ♀. A. Lateral view. B. Metasoma (dorsal view). C. Head. D. Head (SEM). E. Thorax (dorsal view). F. Thorax (dorsal view, SEM). Scale bars: photos: 1 mm, SEM: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3860598" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3860598/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
), b) basitibial plate of female with simple marginal carinae, c) body small, without metasomal hair bands in females and most males, and d) membraneous apicolateral lobes on male S7 (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[616,709,832,859]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="10.[189,232,1932,1958]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,662,1889]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[189,1399,662,1890]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 5. Scrapter albitarsis (Friese, 1909), ♂. A. Lateral view. B. Genitalia (dorsal view, SEM). C. Metasoma (dorsal view). D. S7 (dorsal view, SEM). E. S8, apical end (SEM). F. S8, apical end (SEM). Scale bars: photos: 1 mm, SEM: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3860606" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3860606/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Fig. 5D</figureCitation>
), sometimes reduced to small structures, in nine of the 14 species where the males are known. In other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lepeletier" authorityYear="1841" box="[732,833,868,894]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[732,833,868,894]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Scrapter</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species these lobes, that are a common feature in many colletid genera, are only known in a much more reduced form from some species of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Friese" baseAuthorityYear="1909" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">S. nitidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group. This group also shares the narrow facial fovea and the shape of male genitalia with the &quot;euryglossiform&quot; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lepeletier" authorityYear="1841" box="[398,499,973,999]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[398,499,973,999]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Scrapter</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and might be their closest relatives as 
<bibRefCitation author="Davies G. B. P. &amp; Eardley C. D. &amp; Brothers D. J." box="[950,1182,973,1000]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="141 - 179" refId="ref26814" refString="Davies G. B. P., Eardley C. D. &amp; Brothers D. J. 2005. Eight new species of Scrapter (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Colletidae), with descriptions of S. albifumus and S. amplispinatus females and a major range extension of the genus. African Invertebrates 46: 141 - 179." type="journal article" year="2005">
Davies 
<emphasis box="[1039,1090,973,999]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">et al</emphasis>
. (2005)
</bibRefCitation>
already suggested in their description of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Davies" authorityYear="2005" box="[450,655,1008,1034]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acanthophorus">
<emphasis box="[450,655,1008,1034]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">S. acanthophorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,1399,1073,1135]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
As relationships of species within the &quot;euryglossiform&quot; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lepeletier" authorityYear="1841" box="[891,992,1074,1100]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[891,992,1074,1100]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Scrapter</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are not clear, they are listed in alphabetical order.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,650,1174,1200]" box="[189,650,1174,1200]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,650,1174,1200]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,650,1174,1200]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
Species of &quot;euryglossiform&quot; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lepeletier" authorityYear="1841" box="[547,650,1174,1200]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[547,650,1174,1200]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Scrapter</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
